438. Brix brackets this line, with reference to vv. 364, 378 sqq„ 432. To me it seems that Tyndarus is prolonging the leave—taking as much as he can, and that his reiteration of what he had said before, as well as his unconnected, disordered sentences, are quite in the style of leave—takings in actual life. He labours to impress Philocrates who will soon be beyond call. Scito however must not be translated as if it were memento.
